\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Ch-1, Ex-5.1"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "aluffi51"

\end_inset

 Prove that a final object in a category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 is initial in the opposite category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC^{\mathsf{op}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the final object in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC.$
\end_inset

 Then,
 take any object 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\in\catC^{\mathsf{op}}.$
\end_inset

 Since there is always a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\to I$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

,
 there is a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $I\to Z$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC^{\mathsf{op}}.$
\end_inset

 Siince 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\in\mathsf{C}^{\mathsf{op}}$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary,
 this proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the initial object in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC^{\mathsf{op}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Ch-1, Ex-5.2"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
unique 
\emph default
initial object in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\Obj(\mathsf{Set})$
\end_inset

 is an initial object.
 Then,
 there is a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\emptyset$
\end_inset

 which proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\emptyset.$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Ch-1, Ex-5.3"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Prove that final objects are unique up to isomorphisms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Suppose there are two final objects 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1},F_{2}$
\end_inset

 in a category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC.$
\end_inset

 Then,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}$
\end_inset

 is final,
 we pick the unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:F_{1}\to F_{2}$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

 is final we consider the unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $g:F_{2}\to F_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $fg=1_{F_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}$
\end_inset

 is final,
 so there is only a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{F_{2}}:F_{2}\to F_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $gf$
\end_inset

 must be identical to this.
 By a similar argument we deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula $gf=1_{F_{1}}.$
\end_inset

 This completes the proof that any two final objects 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}$
\end_inset

 are always isomorphic.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Ch-1, Ex-5.4"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 What are the final objects in the category of 'pointed sets' in Eg-3.8?
 Are they unique?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Any singleton 
\begin_inset Formula $\{*\}$
\end_inset

 with the point 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 is a final object.
 Indeed,
 given any object 
\begin_inset Formula $(Z,z)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}^{*}$
\end_inset

 there is obviusly a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma:Z\to\{*\}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(z)=*$
\end_inset

.
 This is clearly the constant map 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\to\{*\}$
\end_inset

.
 Any other singleton set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 with its point 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 forming the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(S,s)$
\end_inset

 would be a final object in this category so such a construction is not unique although obviosuly by a previous exercise it would be unique up to isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Ch-1, Ex-5.5"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 What are the final objects in the category considered in Eg-5.3?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
The final object should be 
\begin_inset Formula $(c:a\mapsto*,\{*\})$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
 in this way,
 given any object 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,Z)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 agrees on equivalent points of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 we get a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma:(f,Z)\to(c,\{*\})$
\end_inset

 that is constant in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 (maps every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

).
 Such a morphism is guaranteed to be unique.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Ch-1, Ex-5.6"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Consider the category corresponding to Eg-3.3 by endowing the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\bZ_{>0}$
\end_inset

 of positive integers with the 
\emph on
divisibility relation.
 
\emph default
Thus,
 there is exactly one morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $d\to m$
\end_inset

 in this category if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 without remainder;
 there is no morphism between 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 Show that this category has products and coproducts.
 What are their conventional names?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
That this construction defines a category is obvious so we will not bother with proving that part.
 Notice that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(a,b)$
\end_inset

 divides both 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 so there are morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd(a,b)\to a,\gcd(a,b)\to b$
\end_inset

.
 Next,
 given any other integer 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 with pairs of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $z\to a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z\to b$
\end_inset

,
 there is a (unique by construction of this category) morhpism 
\begin_inset Formula $z\to\gcd(a,b)$
\end_inset

 simply by definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gcd$
\end_inset

(a,b).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Ch-1, Ex-5.8"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Show that in every category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 the products 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\times A$
\end_inset

 are isomorphic,
 if they exist.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 is a category with objects 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 so that the products 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\times A$
\end_inset

 both exist.
 We denote the canonical projections by 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{A}:A\times B\to A,p_{B}:A\times B\to B,p'_{B}:B\times A\to B,p'_{A}:B\times A\to A$
\end_inset

.
 Next,
 by the universal property of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B$
\end_inset

,
 we get a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:B\times A\to A\times B$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{A}f=p'_{A},p_{B}f=p'_{B}.$
\end_inset

 Next,
 by the universal property of 
\begin_inset Formula $B\times A,$
\end_inset

 there is a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $g:A\times B\to B\times A$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p'_{B}g=p_{B},p'_{A}g=p_{A}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Now,
 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{A}f=p'_{A}gf=p'_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{B}f=p'_{B}gf=p'_{B}.$
\end_inset

 Also,
 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $p'_{B}g=p_{B}fg=p_{B}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p'_{A}g=p_{A}fg=p_{A}.$
\end_inset

 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{B\times A}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $B\times A\to B\times A$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the first two relations the same way as 
\begin_inset Formula $gf$
\end_inset

.
 By uniqueness,
 we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $gf=1_{B\times A}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly,
 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{A\times B}$
\end_inset

 is a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B\to A\times B$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the third and the fourth commutativity relations above the same way as 
\begin_inset Formula $fg$
\end_inset

.
 Once again,
 by uniqueness we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $fg=1_{A\times B}.$
\end_inset

 This completes the proof.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Ch-1, Ex-5.9"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 be a category with products.
 Find a reasonable candidate for the universal property that the product 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B\times C$
\end_inset

 of three objects of 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 ought to satisfy,
 and prove that both 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\times B)\times C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times(B\times C)$
\end_inset

 satisfy this universal property.
 Deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\times B)\times C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\times(B\times C)$
\end_inset

 are necessarily isomorphic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
In any category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 in which binary products are defined,
 there exists an object 
\begin_inset Formula $P\coloneqq\prod^{3}_{i=1}A_{i}$
\end_inset

 and morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi_{i}:P\to A_{i})^{3}_{1}$
\end_inset

 so that for any object 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\in\Obj(\catC)$
\end_inset

 and family of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi_{i}:Z\to A_{i})^{3}_{1}$
\end_inset

 there exists a uniquely defined morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:Z\to P$
\end_inset

 so that the diagram below commutes for every 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq3$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

