\begin_layout Standard
There are three such commutative diagrams for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}=A,A_{2}=B,A_{3}=C$
\end_inset

.
 The commutativity relations are as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{i}\circ\varphi=\varphi_{i},\qquad1\leq i\leq3.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will only show that 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{1}\times A_{2})\times A_{3}$
\end_inset

 satisfies this universal property.
 Indeed,
 notice that there are projections 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi':(A_{1}\times A_{2})\times A_{3}\to(A_{1}\times A_{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{3}:(A_{1}\times A_{2})\times A_{3}\to A_{3}$
\end_inset

 Then,
 suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is any other object with morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi_{i}:Z\to A_{i})^{3}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Next,
 notice that there is a unique morhpism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2}:Z\to A_{1}\times A_{2}$
\end_inset

 by the universal property of the product 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\times A_{2}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi'_{1}\circ(\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2})=\varphi_{1},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi'_{2}\circ(\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2})=\varphi_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'_{1}:(A_{1}\times A_{2})\to A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi'_{2}:(A_{1}\times A_{2})\to A_{2}$
\end_inset

 are the canonical projections of the product 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\times A_{2}$
\end_inset

 to its factors 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 due the the universal property of the binary product 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{1}\times A_{2})\times A_{3}$
\end_inset

,
 there is a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2})\times\varphi_{3}:Z\to(A\times B)\times C$
\end_inset

 so that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi'\circ((\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2})\times\varphi_{3})= & \varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2},\\
\pi_{3}\circ((\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2})\times\varphi_{3})= & \varphi_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{1}\times A_{2})\times A_{3}$
\end_inset

 has projections to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}\coloneqq\pi'_{1}\circ\pi'$
\end_inset

,
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{2}\coloneqq\pi'_{2}\circ\pi'$
\end_inset

 and to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{1}\circ((\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2})\times\varphi_{3})= & \pi'_{1}\circ(\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2})\\
= & \varphi_{1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{2}\circ((\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2})\times\varphi_{3}) & =\pi'_{2}\circ(\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2})\\
 & =\varphi_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the final equality is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{3}\circ((\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2})\times\varphi_{3})=\varphi_{3}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We simply define our 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 to be this morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi_{1}\times\varphi_{2})\times\varphi_{3}$
\end_inset

 and clearly from the above proof it is uniquely defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This completes the proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{1}\times A_{2})\times A_{3}$
\end_inset

 also satisfies the universal property of products of triplets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For uniqueness,
 suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 with the morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho_{i}:Z\to A_{i})^{3}_{1}$
\end_inset

 also satisfies the same universal property.
 Then,
 by universal property of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 there is a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:Z\to P$
\end_inset

 that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}\circ\varphi=\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq3$
\end_inset

.
 Again,
 by universal property of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 there is a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi':P\to Z$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}\circ\varphi'=\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\varphi'=1_{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi'\circ\varphi=1_{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}\circ(\varphi\circ\varphi')=\rho_{i}\circ\varphi'=\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Again,
 by universal property of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{P}$
\end_inset

 is the unique morphism which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}\circ1_{P}=\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

for every 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i3$
\end_inset

.
 This proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ\varphi'=1_{P}.$
\end_inset

 Similarly,
 by invoking universal property of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

,
 we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{Z}$
\end_inset

 is the unique morphism satisfiying 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}\circ1_{Z}=\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 but this means that it must be identical to the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi'\circ\varphi$
\end_inset

 which also satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}\circ(\varphi'\circ\varphi)=\pi_{i}\circ\varphi=\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is unique up to isomorphism.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Ch-1, Ex-5.10"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Push the enveloope a little further still,
 and define products and coproducts for families (i.e.,
 indexed sets) of objects of a category.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
Do these exist in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Suppose we are given a family of objects 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{i})_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 in a category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

.
 An object 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\prod_{I}A_{i}$
\end_inset

 is said to be a product of the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 together with a family of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi_{i}:P\to A_{i})_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 if it satisfies the following universal property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Given any object 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\in\Obj(C)$
\end_inset

 and a family of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho_{i}:Z\to A_{i})_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:Z\to P$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}\circ\varphi=\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Such a 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is uniquely determined up to isomorphisms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
I claim that given a family of sets 
\begin_inset Formula $(A_{i})_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

,
 their generalized cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prod_{i\in I}A_{i}\coloneqq\biggl\{ f:I\to\bigcup_{i\in I}A_{i}\mid f(i)\in A_{i}\text{ for every }i\in I\biggr\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
is the product.
 Notice there are projections 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}:\prod_{i\in I}A_{i}\to A_{i}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}(f)=f(i)$
\end_inset

.
 Given any object 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 with a family of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho_{i}:C\to A_{i})_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 there exists a uniquely defined function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:C\to\prod_{i\in I}A_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}\circ\varphi=\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
 simply define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(c)=f_{c}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{c}(i)=\rho_{i}(c)$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is well defined as a function and satisfies the commutativity relation for every 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 is obvious.
 We are left to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is uniquely defined.
 For this,
 suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi'$
\end_inset

 is another well defined map 
\begin_inset Formula $C\to\prod_{i\in I}A_{i}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}\circ\varphi'=\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\varphi'$
\end_inset

.
 For this,
 take 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in C,$
\end_inset

 then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi'(c))(i)=\pi_{i}(\varphi'(c))=\rho_{i}(c)=\pi_{i}(\varphi(c))=(\varphi(c))(i)$
\end_inset

 and this completes the proof of uniqueness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

